Case Stude 02 - Attrition

Edwin Karabidian

11/23/2021

Executive Summary

DDSAnalytics is an analytics company that specializes in talent management solutions for Fortune 100 companies. The client, Frito Lay company, is seeking the help od DDSAnalytics to analyze and identify causes for employee attrition. Frito Lay would like DDSAnalytics to identify the top three factors that contribute to turnover (backed up by evidence provided by analysis). Frito Lay has provided a dataset for this purpose. This is a dataset of 870 employees information with the following data: ID Age DailyRate DistanceFromHome Education EmployeeCount EmployeeNumber EnvironmentSatisfaction HourlyRate JobInvolvement JobLevel JobSatisfaction MonthlyIncome MonthlyRate NumCompaniesWorked PercentSalaryHike PerformanceRating RelationshipSatisfaction StandardHours StockOptionLevel TotalWorkingYears TrainingTimesLastYear WorkLifeBalance YearsAtCompany YearsInCurrentRole YearsSinceLastPromotion YearsWithCurrManager Attrition

DDSAnalytics constructed 2 models, Nave Bayes and kNN, to predict attrition. After comparing the results, the Nive Bayes was more accurate and it met the Sensitivity and Specificity requirements. Linear Regression Model was used for the salary predictor and it produced an RMSE of 1042.555, satisfying the requirement of <3000.

GLM (Generalized Linear Model) method was used to rank features by importance, Job Involvement, Job Satisfaction, and Number of companies worked.

The following is the detailed analysis of the task.

## Splitting the data in to train and test
AttritionData = read.csv("C:/Users/Karabidian/Documents/SMU_2/Courses/02_Doing Dtat Science/_Case Study 2/_The Work/CaseStudy2-data.csv", header = TRUE)
trainIndices = createDataPartition(AttritionData$Attrition, times = 1, p=0.7, list = FALSE)
trainAttrition = AttritionData[trainIndices,]
testAttrition = AttritionData[-trainIndices,]

## Linear Model for the salary predictor
## Salary depends on the following factors from the data: JobLevel, JobRole, and TotalWorkingYears
## to find the RMSE the RMSE function was used. This was found on https://rdrr.io/cran/qpcR/man/RMSE.html 
## The RMSE requirement for  Salary is RMSE < $3000, By using this function, the linear regression model, Salary_model, has a value of $1055.184.  Hence, the requirement is satisfied.

Salary_model <- lm(MonthlyIncome ~ JobLevel + JobRole + TotalWorkingYears, data = trainAttrition)
summary(Salary_model)
